In [ ]:
predictors = [
    "acousticness", "energy", "instrumentalness", "liveness", "loudness",
    "speechiness", "tempo", "artist_popularity"
]
X = scale(df[predictors])
y = df["hit"].astype("bool")
# Split training data and validating data (70-30 split)
x_train, x_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, y, test_size=0.3)

logisticRegr = LogisticRegression(solver='liblinear', random_state=10)
logisticRegr.fit(x_train, y_train)
y_test_pred = logisticRegr.predict(x_test)
cnf_matrix = metrics.confusion_matrix(y_test, y_test_pred)
print(cnf_matrix)
print(metrics.classification_report(y_test, y_test_pred))
y_pred_proba = logisticRegr.predict_proba(x_test)[::, 1]
fpr, tpr, _ = metrics.roc_curve(y_test, y_pred_proba)
auc = metrics.roc_auc_score(y_test, y_pred_proba)
plt.plot(fpr, tpr, label="data 1, auc=" + str(auc))
plt.legend(loc=4)
plt.show()

  • feature reduction did not improve the permormance

This is due to imbalanced class sample. Next steps.

  • putting weights proportional to the class imbalance
  • re-sample the data to balance positive/negative classes

Method 1a: Using Sklearn "balanced" hyperparameter - uses the values of y to automatically adjust weights

In [ ]:
## Method 1a: Putting weights using skleaern's class_weight parameter
logisticRegr = LogisticRegression(
    solver='liblinear', random_state=10, class_weight='balanced')
logisticRegr.fit(x_train, y_train)
y_test_pred = logisticRegr.predict(x_test)
cnf_matrix = metrics.confusion_matrix(y_test, y_test_pred)
print(cnf_matrix)
print(metrics.classification_report(y_test, y_test_pred))
y_pred_proba = logisticRegr.predict_proba(x_test)[::, 1]
fpr, tpr, _ = metrics.roc_curve(y_test, y_pred_proba)
auc = metrics.roc_auc_score(y_test, y_pred_proba)
plt.plot(fpr, tpr, label="data 1, auc=" + str(auc))
plt.legend(loc=4)
plt.show()

  • very low f1 score BUT definite improvement to prior model

Next: Grid Search for best parameters

In [ ]:
weights = np.linspace(0.05, 0.95, 20)
gsc = GridSearchCV(
    estimator=LogisticRegression(solver='liblinear', random_state=10),
    param_grid={'class_weight': [{
0: x,
1: 1.0 - x
} for x in weights]}, scoring='f1',
cv=3)
grid_result = gsc.fit(x_train, y_train)
print("Best parameters : %s" % grid_result.best_params_)
# Plot the weights vs f1 score
dataz = pd.DataFrame({
    'score': grid_result.cv_results_['mean_test_score'],
    'weight': weights
})
dataz.plot(x='weight')

In [ ]:
## Method 2: Putting calculated weights using grid search
logisticRegr = LogisticRegression(
    solver='liblinear', random_state=10, **grid_result.best_params_)
logisticRegr.fit(x_train, y_train)
y_test_pred = logisticRegr.predict(x_test)
cnf_matrix = metrics.confusion_matrix(y_test, y_test_pred)
print(cnf_matrix)
print(metrics.classification_report(y_test, y_test_pred))
y_pred_proba = logisticRegr.predict_proba(x_test)[::, 1]
fpr, tpr, _ = metrics.roc_curve(y_test, y_pred_proba)
auc = metrics.roc_auc_score(y_test, y_pred_proba)
plt.plot(fpr, tpr, label="data 1, auc=" + str(auc))
plt.legend(loc=4)
plt.show()

  • this model has a higher precision but lower recall

Next: SMOTE re-sampling technique.

In [ ]:
## Method 3: SMOTE
pipe = make_pipeline(SMOTE(),
                     LogisticRegression(solver='liblinear', random_state=10))
# Fit..
pipe.fit(x_train, y_train) # Predict..
y_pred = pipe.predict(x_test)
# Evaluate the model
cnf_matrix = metrics.confusion_matrix(y_test, y_pred)
print(cnf_matrix)
print(metrics.classification_report(y_test, y_pred))
y_pred_proba = pipe.predict_proba(x_test)[::, 1]
fpr, tpr, _ = metrics.roc_curve(y_test, y_pred_proba)
auc = metrics.roc_auc_score(y_test, y_pred_proba)
plt.plot(fpr, tpr, label="data 1, auc=" + str(auc))
plt.legend(loc=4)
plt.show()

  • very similar result to the balanced method

Next: SMOTE in addition to the imbalanced method

In [ ]:
pipe = make_pipeline(SMOTE(),
                     LogisticRegression(solver='liblinear', random_state=10))
weights = np.linspace(0.05, 0.95, 20)
gsc = GridSearchCV(
    estimator=pipe,
param_grid={"smote__sampling_strategy": [x for x in weights]}, scoring='f1',
cv=3)
grid_result = gsc.fit(X, y)
print("Best parameters : %s" % grid_result.best_params_)
## Method 4: SMOTE + optimal ratio
pipe = make_pipeline(
    SMOTE(sampling_strategy=grid_result.
          best_params_["smote__sampling_strategy"]),
    LogisticRegression(solver='liblinear', random_state=10))
# Fit..
pipe.fit(x_train, y_train) # Predict..
y_pred = pipe.predict(x_test)
# Evaluate the model
cnf_matrix = metrics.confusion_matrix(y_test, y_pred)
print(cnf_matrix)
print(metrics.classification_report(y_test, y_pred))
y_pred_proba = pipe.predict_proba(x_test)[::, 1]
fpr, tpr, _ = metrics.roc_curve(y_test, y_pred_proba)
auc = metrics.roc_auc_score(y_test, y_pred_proba)
plt.plot(fpr, tpr, label="data 1, auc=" + str(auc))
plt.legend(loc=4)
plt.show()

  • model also provided similar results to calculated weights method
